{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS 1 plan-review (criterion G6 — approach soundness, anti-patterns & alternative-selection) for the cross-referenced docs plan \"Docs: private-repo credentials, descriptive errors, ref/source semantics, HMAC trust model\" (xref'd here via the EFS/NFS flock caveat in AC5; recorded here as the addressable anchor).\n\nVerdict: PASS. Findings: none.\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (G6):\n- MECHANISM CORRECTNESS: the proposed mechanism — update the existing MCP-setup docs in place to describe the four behavior areas (private-repo fetch credential, descriptive credential-failure + fail-closed-vs-local semantics, ref/source semantics + origin/main default, HMAC trust model + limits + in-toto Statement shape, plus REBAR_GATE_TMPDIR/disk-cap/flock knobs) — is logic-complete for a documentation deliverable. There is no ordering/atomicity/concurrency surface in docs work; the only correctness risk is documenting behavior the code does not actually have, and the plan scopes the behavior areas to those owned by the existing S1-S5 implementation tickets and the already-existing HMAC signing surface (src/rebar/signing.py: HMAC-SHA256 over canonical (ticket_id, manifest), environment-keyed, head_sha freshness binding).\n- FITNESS-FOR-PURPOSE: solves the named problem (operators/agents need clear guidance + clear failures once the snapshot model requires the server to fetch from origin), not a proxy. Each AC maps 1:1 to a Why/What concern.\n- APPROACH SELECTION: I generated two structurally-different alternatives and judged the chosen approach defensible. (1) Fold the credential/trust-model content into code-level docstrings / --help only rather than the setup docs — REJECTED for me to coach: operators standing up a server need standalone setup-doc guidance, not docstrings, so the plan's setup-doc placement is correct. (2) Create a brand-new dedicated trust-model doc page divorced from the setup flow — not clearly superior; the plan's choice to extend the existing setup docs + cross-ref existing artifacts (jira-sync-setup, alto-fruit-punch, signing.py) keeps blast-radius small and aligns with the codebase's existing doc topology (docs/jira-sync-setup.md, docs/config.md). The chosen approach is at-least-as-good on codebase-alignment, blast-radius, and simplicity. Alternatives discarded; not written into the plan.\n- POSITIVE RATIONALE: present — the \"Why\" section states the chosen approach's rationale (the snapshot model adds a fetch-credential operational requirement the old \"read the local checkout\" model lacked, so operators/agents need documented guidance and failures). G6(4) satisfied.\n\nANTI-FP note: docs-only deliverable with a forced, well-understood approach — no manufactured alternatives. No G6 findings."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782522399630951001,"uuid":"4b868afb-8aa5-4c4f-9a3d-094f6bcf019a"}